<h1 style="text-align: center;">Ideal Construction<br>
</h1>

<h2 style="font-weight: normal;"><span style="font-style: italic;">Preface<br>
</span></h2>

<div style="text-align: justify;">Whether it is a machine, vehicle,
building, bridge or any human made object, it must withstand stress and
strain caused by usage: the object must be built by a suitable material
and designed correctly. But even after this we're left with a question
how much material is needed or what material thickness is needed so
that the object will last in use? This question is subject to <span style="font-style: italic;">strength of materials</span> and it is
important, because materials are not free and the less material is
needed, the more space is left for utilization. Think about a house,
whose walls are one meter thick and another house, whose walls are 10
centimeters thick. Which one has bigger rooms?&nbsp;<br>
<br>
In this text we are focusing building construction and specially wood
construction, although in principle the theory to be presented, <span style="font-style: italic;">ideal construction</span>, is applicable
to any material. Wood is a perfect material to build living houses, for
example, but present 2010's production methods raises two obstacles to
prevent large-scale building use of wood:<br>
<ul>
  <li>Wood is an expensive construction material.
Furthermore, the forest resources of the Earth decreases all the time
and the forests left are needed to preserve present ecosystems alive
and to produce the oxygen we all need to breathe.<br>
  </li>
  <li>In order to use present construction methods to build spans
required by ideal construction from wood, we had to use extremely
massive wooden bars, which are both expensive and also they would fill
the space, which is meant for utilization. And furtehrmore, the
carrying capasity of the structure would be low because of massive
wooden balks need to carry their own heavy mass.</li>
</ul>
To use wood as construction material in an environmentally sustainable
way, wood on the market must be goods grown in nursery stock, not wood
of wild. In this case the adequancy and low price of wood can be
guaranteed only if there are several reasons for cultivation of trees,
like using <span style="text-decoration: underline;">tree as an energy
source</span> and <span style="text-decoration: underline;">town
planning</span> and of course the relatively low need for wood, for
which we need the ideal construction. The reader may wonder how to
consume wood for several means would increase the adequancy of wood:
the final answer is found that the existence of the <span style="text-decoration: underline;">republic</span> requires
afforestation of the whole country. Besides, novadays only the bole of
a tree is recovered, but springs, leaves, crust and the rootstock are
abandoned, although they are excellent material for energy production
as are also sawdust and wastewood from wood industry. But let's get to
the heart of the matter so how can we radically reduce the need for
construction wood or any construction material?<br>
</div>

