<br>

<div style="text-align: justify;">We don't use the formulas 1 and 2 in
this text, they are shown only to help the reader to link this text to
the strength of materials in his/her mind. However, it is important to
know, that almost all materials have significantly better endurance
against normal stress (i.e. pulling or pressing) than against shear or
bending stress. But wood is an exceptional material in the sense that
its flexural strength and tensile strength are usually up to two times
bigger than compressive strength while shear strength is only one tenth
compared to the tensile strength (this is the case along the grain of
wood, but not across the grain). I'm going to concentrate on
compressive strength in this text, because the idea of the ideal
construction is to transform all shear stress to compression. Wood has
significant compressive strength along the grain reaching the same
level than concrete: the compressive strength of wood varies from
species to species between 40 - 100 MPa while the typical compressive
strength of concrete is between 30 - 80 MPa and some fiber reinforced
special concretes are between 150 - 250 MPa.<br>
</div>

