<div style="text-align: justify;">A construction is called as an ideal
construction, if it experiences purely and only compression or tension.
For example the aqueduct in figure 3 experiences only compression. This
is possible by building arch vaults, but the problems of an arch vault
are it takes space, it is difficult to build and it is primitive as a
whole. If we compare it to the parking garage of figure 4, we can
notice, that a straight vault gives both more space and savings on
material costs, albeit that parking garage is not an ideal
construction: there's both normal and shear stresses existing. But is
possible to build a building like the parking garage of figure 4 such a
way it wold be an ideal consturction? The answer is that by using
stressed tendons mainly yes, but the details shown by the figure 4
makes the complete ideal construction impossible: shear stresses
experienced by concrete cannot be avoided. But this text introduces an
example of an <a href="C#Frame_of_Sampo">ideal construction</a>, which has straight vaults and whose material and space consumption is as effective as is on the parking garage in figure 4.<br>
